 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 709<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/18/02 9:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=48.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Atomic Car?</span><hr size=1> They certainly were dreamers back then. I can just imagine people buying Uranium at their local Shell fuel station. We certainly wouldn't need so many of them and the Arab Sheiks would all be penniless. Still taxing goatherders to scrape a living.<br>
People would travel more and cars would be built bigger, heavier and more rugged to support the shielding. That would suit Americans in particular who like big cars. They would be a lot safer than the tin foil plastic things made today. A tiny scratch costs hundreds of dollars and in an accident they just disintegrate. Atomic cars would be solid.<br>
If it were possible to do then I would vote for it. The only arguments against an atomic car are environmental risk and terrorism. You need a reactor to upgrade Uranium for weapon use and the waste could be stored and collected for breeder stations. They would be less polluting than fossil fuel cars. Accidents could be avoided by making the shielding serve the dual purpose of both radiation and impact protection. Like with RTG's which fall many kilometres to hard ground unscathed. You can even blow them up. I wonder how many parallel universes exist where drivers only refuel their cars annually. <br>
This is all fanciful thinking but one has to wonder what might have been. The potential of nuclear power hasn't even begun to be explored.  <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!

<br><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace">NUCLEARSPACE</a>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 72<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/18/02 11:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=48.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Atomic Car?</span><hr size=1> Around this time, the US Army displayed models of an atomic powered tank at some of its PR extravaganzas. I don't know how serious the project was, but it looked like a Sherman tank with an extra-large rear deck, a lot like the Nucleon. It would have some fairly obvious disadvantages for a combat vehicle. <br>
<br>
I sent the Nucleon article to a friend who sells cars. He says that he still prefers &quot;witch-burning&quot; cars. This gives me an idea: Can someone design a druid-burning car? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A> at: 3/18/02 11:35:21 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 368<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/19/02 6:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=48.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Atomic Car?</span><hr size=1> The biggest problem with solid cars is the lack of a crumple zone.<br>
<br>
It's really good to have a crumple zone because that way if you crash you won't get as much force on you during the collision.<br>
<br>
As for tin foil plastic things.  Our cars are still mostly metal although there are some fiberglass cars coming out. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 752<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/22/02 10:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=48.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Atomic Car?</span><hr size=1> I don't know a great deal about cars but this reminds me of a scene from the movie Back to the Future 2 when the Delorean is chasing down Biff(was that the bullies name?) and Marty asks.<br>
&quot;Why don't we just block the road.&quot;<br>
the professor replies.<br>
&quot;That 50's car would go through a modern Delorean like it was Tinfoil.&quot;<br>
<br>
Maybe they built cars harder and heavier back in the 50's because it was assumed safer to the passengers. the crumpling effect wasn't considered. I'm not sure it's really of much help to Van drivers or those in small cars. Motorbike riders can just kiss their lives goodbye in a hard collision.<br>
<br>
Truck drivers rarely die in a crash with other vehicles but have nothing much in front to protect them against say a wall. <br>
<br>
Why not have a big heavy nuclear car with a sturdy frame and crumpling area around it. Not unlike a bumper car. Shock absorbers all around. They might be as long as limousines and we might have to build bigger roads but any new vehicle takes decades to become mainstream transportation. Just as we developed from Horse and Carriage Roads to enormous Autobahns. <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
