</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 386<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/23/02 2:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=48.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Atomic Car?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Maybe they built cars harder and heavier back in the 50's because it was assumed safer to the passengers.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Back in the '50's &quot;safe car&quot; was an oxymoron.  Car makers didn't seem to even know what safety was and no one really cared about it.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> the crumpling effect wasn't considered. I'm not sure it's really of much help to Van drivers or those in small cars.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
They can still put crumple zones in vans and small cars although not as long as a big passenger car.  Those cars need to rely on other safety features along with better drivers (unlike those 4 wheel drive monstronities which should be banned from people who don't take them off road).<br>
<br>
In general though you are safer in a larger car then a smaller one due to increased mass and more crumple zones.  Besides the bigger cars tend to be more expensive and also tend to have more safety systems.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Truck drivers rarely die in a crash with other vehicles but have nothing much in front to protect them against say a wall. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
